07402nam a22009855i 9789048551040DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485510407 a10.1515/97890485510402doi  a(DE-B1597)649556  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aQ183.E85bL33 2023 7aHIS0100202bisacsh04a507.1/14223/eng/2023051104aThe Laboratory Revolution and the Creation of the Modern University, 1830-1940 /ced. by Klaas Berkel, Ernst Homburg. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (346 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History of Knowledge ;v500tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tList of Figures and Charts -- tPreface -- tPart I The Laboratory Revolution: Origins and Impact -- t1 The Joint Emergence of the Teaching-Research Laboratory and the Modern University: An Introduction -- t2 Origins and Spread of the ‘Giessen Model’ in University Science -- t3 The Laboratory Ethos, 1850–1900 -- tPart II Laboratory Networks -- t4 Chemistry in Zürich, 1833–1930 : Developing the Teaching- Research Laboratory in the Swiss Context -- t5 Island Kingdoms in the Making : The New Laboratories and the Fragmentation of Dutch Universities c.1900 -- t6 A Fertile Ecosystem : University Chemical Laboratories and their Suppliers in Fin-de-Siècle Paris -- t7 Fighting for Modern Teaching and Research Laboratories in Norway : The Chemistry Laboratory in Political Dispute around 1920 -- t8 Religion and the Laboratory Revolution : Towards a Physiological Laboratory at a Calvinist University in the Netherlands, 1880–1924 -- tPart III Laboratory Values -- t9 Aspects of the Social Organization of the Chemical Laboratory in Heidelberg and Imperial College, London -- t10 Of Growing Significance : The Support Staff in the Laboratories and Institutes of Utrecht University during the Interwar Period -- t11 A Revolution in Genetics at Gendered Experimental Venues : Cambridge and Berlin, 1890–1930 -- t12 Serialized Laboratories : Laboratory Journals and the Making of Modern Science and Scientific Publishing, 1840s–1950s -- t13 Images of the Laboratory in the Popular Press -- tAcknowledgements -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe modern research university originated in Europe in the second half of the nineteenth century, largely due to the creation and expansion of the teaching and research laboratory. The universities and the sciences underwent a laboratory revolution that fundamentally changed the nature of both. This revolutionary development began in chemistry, where Justus Liebig is credited with systematically employing his students in his ongoing research during the 1830s. Later, this development spread to other fields, including the social sciences and the humanities. The consequences for the universities were colossal. The expansion of the laboratories demanded extensive new building programs, reshaping the outlook of the university. The social structure of the university also diversified because of this laboratory expansion, while what it meant to be a scientist changed dramatically. This volume explores the spatial, social, and cultural dimensions of the rise of the modern research laboratory within universities and their consequent reshaping.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEducation, HigherzEuropexHistory. 0aLaboratorieszEuropexHistory. 0aSciencezEuropexHistory. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 4aScience and Technology. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Western.2bisacsh  aLaboratory, University, Division of Labour, Scientific Research Architecture.1 aBerkel, Klaas van, eco